.TH megaco 3 "megaco 4.8.3" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
megaco \- Main API of the Megaco application

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Interface module for the Megaco application

.SH DATA TYPES
.LP
.B
\fBaction_reply() :: megaco_encoder:action_reply().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBaction_reps() :: [action_reply()].\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBaction_reqs() :: binary() | [action_request()].\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBaction_request() :: megaco_encoder:action_request().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBconn_handle() :: megaco_user:conn_handle().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBconn_info_item() ::\fR
\fB          control_pid | send_handle | local_mid | remote_mid |\fR
\fB          receive_handle | trans_id | max_trans_id | request_timer |\fR
\fB          long_request_timer | request_keep_alive_timeout |\fR
\fB          long_request_resend | reply_timer | call_proxy_gc_timeout |\fR
\fB          auto_ack | trans_ack | trans_ack_maxcount | trans_req |\fR
\fB          trans_req_maxcount | trans_req_maxsize | trans_timer |\fR
\fB          pending_timer | sent_pending_limit | recv_pending_limit |\fR
\fB          send_mod | encoding_mod | encoding_config | protocol_version |\fR
\fB          strict_version | reply_data | threaded | resend_indication |\fR
\fB          segment_reply_ind | segment_recv_timer | segment_send |\fR
\fB          max_pdu_size.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
This type is a basic (atom) lookup key (for info on an active connection). The corresponding value can be of any type.

control_pid
.RS 2
The process identifier of the controlling process for a connection.

.PP
Value type: pid()


.RE

send_handle
.RS 2
Opaque send handle whose contents is internal for the send module.

.PP
Value type: \fIsend_handle/0\fR


.RE

local_mid
.RS 2
The local mid (of the connection, i.e. the own mid).

.PP
Value type: \fImid/0\fR


.RE

remote_mid
.RS 2
The remote mid (of the connection).

.PP
Value type: \fImid/0\fR


.RE

receive_handle
.RS 2
Construct a megaco_receive_handle record.

.PP
Value type: \fIreceive_handle/0\fR


.RE

trans_id
.RS 2
Next transaction id.

.PP
Note that transaction id's are (currently) maintained on a per user basis so there is no way to be sure that the value returned will actually be used for a transaction sent on this connection (in case a user has several connections, which is not at all unlikely).

.PP
Value type: \fItransaction_id/0\fR | \fIundefined_serial\fR


.RE

max_trans_id
.RS 2
Last transaction id.

.PP
Value type: \fItransaction_id/0\fR | \fIinfinity\fR


.RE

request_timer
.RS 2
Wait for reply.

.PP
The timer is cancelled when a reply is received.

.PP
When a pending message is received, the timer is cancelled and the \fIlong_request_timer\fR is started instead (see below). No resends will be performed from this point (since we now know that the other side has received the request).

.PP
When the timer reaches an intermediate expire, the request is resent and the timer is restarted.

.PP
When the timer reaches the final expire, either the function \fImegaco:call\fR will return with \fI{error, timeout}\fR or the callback function \fIhandle_trans_reply\fR will be called with \fIUserReply = {error, timeout}\fR (if \fImegaco:cast\fR was used).

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI#megaco_incr_timer{}\fR.


.RE

long_request_timer
.RS 2
Wait for reply after having received a pending message.

.PP
When the timer reaches an intermediate expire, the timer restarted.

.PP
When a pending message is received, and the \fIlong_request_timer\fR is \fInot\fR "on its final leg", the timer will be restarted, and, if \fIlong_request_resend = true\fR, the request will be re-sent.

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI60 seconds\fR.


.RE

request_keep_alive_timeout
.RS 2
Specifies the timeout time for the request-keep-alive timer.

.PP
This timer is started when the \fIfirst\fR reply to an asynchronous request (issued using the \fImegaco:cast/3\fR function) arrives. As long as this timer is running, replies will be delivered via the handle_trans_reply/4,5 callback function, with their "arrival number" (see \fIUserReply\fR of the handle_trans_reply/4,5 callback function).

.PP
Replies arriving after the timer has expired, will be delivered using the handle_unexpected_trans/3,4 callback function.

.PP
Value type: \fIplain\fR | non_neg_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fIplain\fR.


.RE

long_request_resend
.RS 2
This option indicates weather the request should be resent until the reply is received, 
\fIeven\fR though a pending message has been received.
.PP
Normally, after a pending message has been received, the request is not resent (since a pending message is an indication that the request has been received). But since the reply (to the request) can be lost, this behaviour has its values.

.PP
It is of course pointless to set this value to \fItrue\fR unless the \fIlong_request_timer\fR (see above) is also set to an incremental timer (\fI#megaco_incr_timer{}\fR).

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

reply_timer
.RS 2
Wait for an ack.

.PP
When a request is received, some info related to the reply is store internally (e.g. the binary of the reply). This info will live until either an ack is received or this timer expires. For instance, if the same request is received again (e.g. a request with the same transaction id), the (stored) reply will be (re-) sent automatically by megaco.

.PP
If the timer is of type \fI#megaco_incr_timer{}\fR, then for each intermediate timout, the reply will be resent (this is valid until the ack is received or the timer expires).

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI30000\fR.


.RE

call_proxy_gc_timeout
.RS 2
Timeout time for the call proxy.

.PP
When a request is sent using the \fIcall/3\fR function, a proxy process is started to handle all replies. When the reply has been received and delivered to the user, the proxy process continue to exist for as long as this option specifies. Any received messages, is passed on to the user via the handle_unexpected_trans callback function.

.PP
The timeout time is in milliseconds. A value of 0 (zero) means that the proxy process will exit directly after the reply has been delivered.

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI5000\fR (= 5 seconds).


.RE

auto_ack
.RS 2
Automatic send transaction ack when the transaction reply has been received (see 
\fItrans_ack\fR below).
.PP
This is used for \fIthree-way-handshake\fR.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

trans_ack
.RS 2
Shall ack's be accumulated or not.

.PP
This property is only valid if \fIauto_ack\fR is true.

.PP
If \fIauto_ack\fR is true, then if \fItrans_ack\fR is \fIfalse\fR, ack's will be sent immediately. If \fItrans_ack\fR is \fItrue\fR, then ack's will instead be sent to the transaction sender process for accumulation and later sending (see \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxsize\fR, \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR and \fItrans_timer\fR).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

trans_ack_maxcount
.RS 2
Maximum number of accumulated ack's. At most this many ack's will be accumulated by the transaction sender (if started and configured to accumulate ack's).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI10\fR.


.RE

trans_req
.RS 2
Shall requests be accumulated or not.

.PP
If \fItrans_req\fR is \fIfalse\fR, then request(s) will be sent immediately (in its own message).

.PP
If \fItrans_req\fR is true, then request(s) will instead be sent to the transaction sender process for accumulation and later sending (see \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxsize\fR, \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR and \fItrans_timer\fR).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

trans_req_maxcount
.RS 2
Maximum number of accumulated requests. At most this many requests will be accumulated by the transaction sender (if started and configured to accumulate requests).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI10\fR.


.RE

trans_req_maxsize
.RS 2
Maximum size of the accumulated requests. At most this much requests will be accumulated by the transaction sender (if started and configured to accumulate requests).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI2048\fR.


.RE

trans_timer
.RS 2
Transaction sender timeout time. Has two functions. First, if the value is 0, then transactions will not be accumulated (e.g. the transaction sender process will not be started). Second, if the value is greater then 0 and 
\fIauto_ack\fR and \fItrans_ack\fR is true or if \fItrans_req\fR is true, then transaction sender will be started and transactions (which is depending on the values of \fIauto_ack\fR, \fItrans_ack\fR and \fItrans_req\fR) will be accumulated, for later sending.
.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI0\fR.


.RE

pending_timer
.RS 2
Automatic send transaction pending if the timer expires before a transaction reply has been sent. This timer is also called provisional response timer.

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI30000\fR (= 30 seconds).


.RE

sent_pending_limit
.RS 2
Sent pending limit (see the MGOriginatedPendingLimit and the MGCOriginatedPendingLimit of the megaco root package). This parameter specifies how many pending messages that can be sent (for a given received transaction request). When the limit is exceeded, the transaction is aborted (see handle_trans_request_abort) and an error message is sent to the other side.

.PP
Note that this has no effect on the actual sending of pending transactions. This is either implicit (e.g. when receiving a re-sent transaction request for a request which is being processed) or controlled by the pending_timer, see above.

.PP
Value type: pos_integer() | \fIinfinity\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE

recv_pending_limit
.RS 2
Receive pending limit (see the MGOriginatedPendingLimit and the MGCOriginatedPendingLimit of the megaco root package). This parameter specifies how many pending messages that can be received (for a sent transaction request). When the limit is exceeded, the transaction is considered lost, and an error returned to the user (through the call-back function 
\fIhandle_trans_reply\fR).
.PP
Value type: pos_integer() | \fIinfinity\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE

send_mod
.RS 2
Send callback module which exports send_message/2. The function SendMod:send_message(SendHandle, Binary) is invoked when the bytes needs to be transmitted to the remote user.

.PP
Value type: module().

.PP
Defaults to \fImegaco_tcp\fR.


.RE

encoding_mod
.RS 2
Encoding callback module which exports encode_message/2 and decode_message/2. The function EncodingMod:encode_message(EncodingConfig, MegacoMessage) is invoked whenever a 'MegacoMessage' record needs to be translated into an Erlang binary. The function EncodingMod:decode_message(EncodingConfig, Binary) is invoked whenever an Erlang binary needs to be translated into a 'MegacoMessage' record.

.PP
Value type: module().

.PP
Defaults to \fImegaco_pretty_text_encoder\fR.


.RE

encoding_config
.RS 2
Encoding module config.

.PP
Value type: loist().

.PP
Defaults to \fI[]\fR.


.RE

protocol_version
.RS 2
Actual protocol version.

.PP
Value type: \fIprotocol_version/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI1\fR.


.RE

strict_version
.RS 2
Strict version control, i.e. when a message is received, verify that the version is that which was negotiated.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fItrue\fR.


.RE

reply_data
.RS 2
Default reply data.

.PP
Value type: term()

.PP
Defaults to \fIundefined\fR.


.RE

threaded
.RS 2
If a received message contains several transaction requests, this option indicates whether the requests should be handled sequentially in the same process (
\fIfalse\fR), or if each request should be handled by its own process (\fItrue\fR i.e. a separate process is spawned for each request).
.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

resend_indication
.RS 2
This option indicates weather the transport module should be told if a message send is a resend or not.

.PP
If \fIfalse\fR, megaco messages are sent using the send_message/2 function.

.PP
If \fItrue\fR, megaco message \fIre-sends\fR are made using the resend_message function. The initial message send is still done using the send_message function.

.PP
The special value \fIflag\fR instead indicates that the function send_message/3 shall be used.

.PP
Value type: \fIflag\fR | boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

segment_reply_ind
.RS 2
This option specifies if the user shall be notified of received segment replies or not.

.PP
See handle_segment_reply callback function for more information.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

segment_recv_timer
.RS 2
This timer is started when the segment indicated by the 
\fIsegmentation complete token\fR (e.g. the last of the segment which makes up the reply) is received, but all segments has not yet been received.
.PP
When the timer finally expires, a "megaco segments not received" (459) error message is sent to the other side and the user is notified with a \fIsegment timeout\fR \fIUserReply\fR in either the handle_trans_reply callback function or the return value of the \fIcall/2\fR function.

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI10000\fR (= 10 seconds).


.RE

segment_send
.RS 2
Shall outgoing messages be segmented or not.

.PP
Value type: \fInone\fR | pos_integer() | \fIinfinity\fR

none
.RS 2
Do not segment outgoing reply messages. This is useful when either it is known that messages are never to large or that the transport protocol can handle such things on its own (e.g. TCP or SCTP).


.RE

pos_integer/0
.RS 2
Outgoing reply messages will be segmented as needed (see 
\fImax_pdu_size\fR below). This value, K, indicate the outstanding window, i.e. how many segments can be outstanding (not acknowledged) at any given time.

.RE

infinity
.RS 2
Outgoing reply messages will be segmented as needed (see 
\fImax_pdu_size\fR below). Segment messages are sent all at once (i.e. no acknowledgement awaited before sending the next segment).

.RE

.PP
Defaults to \fInone\fR.


.RE

max_pdu_size
.RS 2
Max message size. If the encoded message (PDU) exceeds this size, the message should be segmented, and then encoded.

.PP
Value type: \fIinfinity\fR | pos_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE


