.RE
.B
\fBsystem_info_item() ::\fR
\fB          text_config | connections | users | n_active_requests |\fR
\fB          n_active_replies | n_active_connections | reply_counters |\fR
\fB          pending_counters.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
System info items.

text_config
.RS 2
The text encoding config.

.PP
Value type: term()


.RE

connections
.RS 2
Lists all active connections. Returns a list of megaco_conn_handle records.

.PP
Value type: [\fIconn_handle/0\fR]


.RE

users
.RS 2
Lists all active users.

.PP
Value type: [\fImid/0\fR]


.RE

n_active_requests
.RS 2
Returns number of requests that has originated from this Erlang node and still are active (and therefore consumes system resources).

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()


.RE

n_active_replies
.RS 2
Returns the number of replies that has originated from this Erlang node and still are active (and therefore consumes system resources).

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()


.RE

n_active_connections
.RS 2
Returns the number of active connections.

.PP
Value type: non_neg_integer()


.RE

reply_counters
.RS 2
Returns a list of the reply counters.

.PP
Value type: {\fIconn_handle/0\fR, \fItransaction_id/0\fR, [non_neg_integer()}]


.RE

pending_counters
.RS 2
Returns a list of the receive and sent pending counters.

.PP
Value type: {recv | sent, [{\fItransaction_id/0\fR, [non_neg_integer()}]}]


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_data() :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The trace data passed to the trace handler fun (in the second argument) and returned by same. For instance this could be a file descriptor, that the trace handler fun can use to print the event to a file.


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_event() :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The trace event generated by dbg.


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_handler() ::\fR
\fB          fun((trace_event(), trace_data()) -> trace_data()).\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The trace handler fun is used to "process" each trace event (for instance print to file or to stdout after formating).


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_level() :: min | max | 0..100.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
How much trace events should be produced. \fImin\fR (=\fI0\fR) means no trace events are produced, which is the default.


