.PP
If the timer is of type \fI#megaco_incr_timer{}\fR, then for each intermediate timout, the reply will be resent (this is valid until the ack is received or the timer expires).

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI30 seconds\fR.


.RE

request_keep_alive_timeout
.RS 2
Specifies the timeout time for the request-keep-alive timer.

.PP
This timer is started when the \fIfirst\fR reply to an asynchronous request (issued using the \fImegaco:cast/3\fR function) arrives. As long as this timer is running, replies will be delivered via the handle_trans_reply/4,5 callback function, with their "arrival number" (see \fIUserReply\fR of the handle_trans_reply/4,5 callback function).

.PP
Replies arriving after the timer has expired, will be delivered using the handle_unexpected_trans/3,4 callback function.

.PP
Value type: \fIplain\fR | non_neg_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fIplain\fR.


.RE

call_proxy_gc_timeout
.RS 2
Timeout time for the call proxy.

.PP
When a request is sent using the \fIcall/3\fR function, a proxy process is started to handle all replies. When the reply has been received and delivered to the user, the proxy process continue to exist for as long as this option specifies. Any received messages, is passed on to the user via the handle_unexpected_trans callback function.

.PP
The timeout time is in milliseconds. A value of 0 (zero) means that the proxy process will exit directly after the reply has been delivered.

.PP
Value type: pos_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI5000\fR (= 5 seconds).


.RE

auto_ack
.RS 2
Automatic send transaction ack when the transaction reply has been received (see 
\fItrans_ack\fR below).
.PP
This is used for \fIthree-way-handshake\fR.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

trans_ack
.RS 2
Shall ack's be accumulated or not.

.PP
This property is only valid if \fIauto_ack\fR is true.

.PP
If \fIauto_ack\fR is true, then if \fItrans_ack\fR is \fIfalse\fR, ack's will be sent immediately. If \fItrans_ack\fR is \fItrue\fR, then ack's will instead be sent to the transaction sender process for accumulation and later sending (see \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxsize\fR, \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR and \fItrans_timer\fR).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

trans_ack_maxcount
.RS 2
Maximum number of accumulated ack's. At most this many ack's will be accumulated by the transaction sender (if started and configured to accumulate ack's).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI10\fR.


.RE

trans_req
.RS 2
Shall requests be accumulated or not.

.PP
If \fItrans_req\fR is \fIfalse\fR, then request(s) will be sent immediately (in its own message).

.PP
If \fItrans_req\fR is true, then request(s) will instead be sent to the transaction sender process for accumulation and later sending (see \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxcount\fR, \fItrans_req_maxsize\fR, \fItrans_ack_maxcount\fR and \fItrans_timer\fR).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

trans_req_maxcount
.RS 2
Maximum number of accumulated requests. At most this many requests will be accumulated by the transaction sender (if started and configured to accumulate requests).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI10\fR.


.RE

trans_req_maxsize
.RS 2
Maximum size of the accumulated requests. At most this much requests will be accumulated by the transaction sender (if started and configured to accumulate requests).

.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI2048\fR.


.RE

trans_timer
.RS 2
Transaction sender timeout time. Has two functions. First, if the value is 0, then transactions will not be accumulated (e.g. the transaction sender process will not be started). Second, if the value is greater then 0 and 
\fIauto_ack\fR and \fItrans_ack\fR are both true or if \fItrans_req\fR is true, then transaction sender will be started and transactions (which is depending on the values of \fIauto_ack\fR, \fItrans_ack\fR and \fItrans_req\fR) will be accumulated, for later sending.
.PP
See also transaction sender for more info.

.PP
Value type: integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fI0\fR.


.RE

pending_timer
.RS 2
Automatically send pending if the timer expires before a transaction reply has been sent. This timer is also called provisional response timer.

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI30000\fR.


.RE

sent_pending_limit
.RS 2
Sent pending limit (see the MGOriginatedPendingLimit and the MGCOriginatedPendingLimit of the megaco root package). This parameter specifies how many pending messages that can be sent (for a given received transaction request). When the limit is exceeded, the transaction is aborted (see handle_trans_request_abort) and an error message is sent to the other side.

.PP
Note that this has no effect on the actual sending of pending transactions. This is either implicit (e.g. when receiving a re-sent transaction request for a request which is being processed) or controlled by the pending_timer, see above.

.PP
Value type: \fIinfinity\fR | pos_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE

recv_pending_limit
.RS 2
Receive pending limit (see the MGOriginatedPendingLimit and the MGCOriginatedPendingLimit of the megaco root package). This parameter specifies how many pending messages that can be received (for a sent transaction request). When the limit is exceeded, the transaction is considered lost, and an error returned to the user (through the call-back function 
\fIhandle_trans_reply\fR).
.PP
Value type: \fIinfinity\fR | pos_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE

send_mod
.RS 2
Send callback module which exports send_message/2. The function SendMod:send_message(SendHandle, Binary) is invoked when the bytes needs to be transmitted to the remote user.

.PP
Value type: module()

.PP
Defaults to \fImegaco_tcp\fR.


.RE

encoding_mod
.RS 2
Encoding callback module which exports encode_message/2 and decode_message/2. The function EncodingMod:encode_message(EncodingConfig, MegacoMessage) is invoked whenever a 'MegacoMessage' record needs to be translated into an Erlang binary. The function EncodingMod:decode_message(EncodingConfig, Binary) is invoked whenever an Erlang binary needs to be translated into a 'MegacoMessage' record.

.PP
Value type: module()

.PP
Defaults to \fImegaco_pretty_text_encoder\fR.


.RE

encoding_config
.RS 2
Encoding module config.

.PP
Value type: list()

.PP
Defaults to \fI[]\fR.


.RE

protocol_version
.RS 2
Actual protocol version.

.PP
Value type: \fIprotocol_version/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI1\fR.


.RE

strict_version
.RS 2
Strict version control, i.e. when a message is received, verify that the version is that which was negotiated.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fItrue\fR.


.RE

reply_data
.RS 2
Default reply data.

.PP
Value type: term()

.PP
Defaults to \fIundefined\fR.


.RE

user_mod
.RS 2
Name of the user callback module. See the the reference manual for megaco_user for more info.

.PP
Value type: module()

.PP
Has no default value since its an mandatory config option.


.RE

user_args
.RS 2
List of extra arguments to the user callback functions. See the the reference manual for megaco_user for more info.

.PP
Value type: list()


.RE

threaded
.RS 2
If a received message contains several transaction requests, this option indicates whether the requests should be handled sequentially in the same process (
\fIfalse\fR), or if each request should be handled by its own process (\fItrue\fR i.e. a separate process is spawned for each request).
.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

resend_indication
.RS 2
This option indicates weather the transport module should be told if a message send is a resend or not.

.PP
If \fIfalse\fR, megaco messages are sent using the send_message function.

.PP
If \fItrue\fR, megaco message \fIre-sends\fR are made using the resend_message function. The initial message send is still done using the send_message function.

.PP
The special value \fIflag\fR instead indicates that the function send_message/3 shall be used.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

segment_reply_ind
.RS 2
This option specifies if the user shall be notified of received segment replies or not.

.PP
See handle_segment_reply callback function for more information.

.PP
Value type: boolean()

.PP
Defaults to \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

segment_recv_timer
.RS 2
This timer is started when the segment indicated by the 
\fIsegmentation complete token\fR is received, but all segments has not yet been received.
.PP
When the timer finally expires, a "megaco segments not received" (459) error message is sent to the other side and the user is notified with a \fIsegment timeout\fR \fIUserReply\fR in either the handle_trans_reply callback function or the return value of the \fIcall/3\fR function.

.PP
Value type: \fImegaco_timer/0\fR

.PP
Defaults to \fI10000\fR.


.RE

segment_send
.RS 2
Shall outgoing messages be segmented or not.

.PP
Value type: \fInone\fR | pos_integer() | \fIinfinity\fR

none
.RS 2
Do not segment outgoing reply messages. This is useful when either it is known that messages are never to large or that the transport protocol can handle such things on its own (e.g. TCP or SCTP).


.RE

pos_integer/0
.RS 2
Outgoing reply messages will be segmented as needed (see 
\fImax_pdu_size\fR below). This value, K, indicate the outstanding window, i.e. how many segments can be outstanding (not acknowledged) at any given time.

.RE

infinity
.RS 2
Outgoing reply messages will be segmented as needed (see 
\fImax_pdu_size\fR below). Segment messages are sent all at once (i.e. no acknowledgement awaited before sending the next segment).

.RE

.PP
Defaults to \fInone\fR.


.RE

max_pdu_size
.RS 2
Max message size. If the encoded message (PDU) exceeds this size, the message should be segmented, and then encoded.

.PP
Value type: \fIinfinity\fR | pos_integer()

.PP
Defaults to \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE


.RE
.B
\fBvoid() :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The type is used when a functions return is to be ignored.


.RE
.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBcall(ConnHandle, ActionRequests, SendOptions) ->\fR
\fB              {ProtocolVersion, UserReply | [UserReply]}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  ConnHandle :: conn_handle(),\fR
\fB                  ActionRequests :: action_reqs() | [action_reqs()],\fR
\fB                  SendOptions :: [SendOption],\fR
\fB                  SendOption ::\fR
\fB                      {request_timer, megaco_timer()} |\fR
\fB                      {long_request_timer, megaco_timer()} |\fR
\fB                      {send_handle, send_handle()} |\fR
\fB                      {protocol_version, protocol_version()} |\fR
\fB                      {call_proxy_gc_timeout, non_neg_integer()},\fR
\fB                  ProtocolVersion :: protocol_version(),\fR
\fB                  UserReply :: Success | Failure,\fR
\fB                  Success :: {ok, Result} | {ok, Result, SuccessExtra},\fR
\fB                  Result :: MessageResult | SegmentResult,\fR
\fB                  MessageResult :: action_reps(),\fR
\fB                  SegmentResult :: SegmentsOk,\fR
\fB                  SegmentsOk :: [{segment_no(), action_reps()}],\fR
\fB                  Failure ::\fR
\fB                      {error, Reason} | {error, Reason, ErrorExtra},\fR
\fB                  Reason ::\fR
\fB                      MessageReason | SegmentReason | UserCancelReason |\fR
\fB                      SendReason | OtherReason,\fR
\fB                  MessageReason :: error_desc(),\fR
\fB                  SegmentReason ::\fR
\fB                      {segment, SegmentsOk, SegmentsErr} |\fR
\fB                      {segment_timeout, MissingSegments, SegmentsOk,\fR
\fB                       SegmentsErr},\fR
\fB                  SegmentsErr :: {segment_no(), error_desc()},\fR
\fB                  MissingSegments :: [segment_no()],\fR
\fB                  UserCancelReason :: {user_cancel, ReasonForUserCancel},\fR
\fB                  ReasonForUserCancel :: term(),\fR
\fB                  SendReason :: SendCancelledReason | SendFailedReason,\fR
\fB                  SendCancelledReason ::\fR
\fB                      {send_message_cancelled, term()},\fR
\fB                  SendFailedReason :: {send_message_failed, term()},\fR
\fB                  OtherReason ::\fR
\fB                      {wrong_mid,\fR
\fB                       WrongMid :: mid(),\fR
\fB                       RightMid :: mid(),\fR
\fB                       transaction_reply()} |\fR
\fB                      term(),\fR
\fB                  SuccessExtra :: term(),\fR
\fB                  ErrorExtra :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Sends one or more transaction request(s) and waits for the reply.

.PP
When sending one transaction in a message, \fIActionRequests\fR should be \fIaction_reqs/0\fR (the reply will then be \fIUserReply\fR). When sending several transactions in a message, \fIActionRequests\fR should be \fI[action_reqs()]\fR (the reply will then be \fI[UserReply]\fR). Each element of the list is part of one transaction.

.PP
For some of \fIour\fR codecs (not binary), it is also possible to pre-encode the actions, in which case \fIActionRequests\fR will be either a \fIbinary/0\fR or \fI[binary()]\fR.

.PP
The function returns when the reply arrives, when the request timer eventually times out or when the outstanding requests are explicitly cancelled.

.PP
The default values of the send options are obtained by \fImegaco:conn_info(ConnHandle, Item)\fR. But the send options above, may explicitly be overridden.

.PP
The \fIProtocolVersion\fR version is the version actually encoded in the reply message.

.PP
At \fISuccess\fR, the \fIUserReply\fR contains a list of 'ActionReply' records possibly containing error indications.

.PP
A \fIFailure\fR, indicates that the remote user has replied with an explicit transactionError.

.PP
A \fIUserCancelReason\fR, indicates that the request has been canceled by the user. \fIReasonForUserCancel\fR is the reason given in the call to the \fIcancel/2\fR function.

.PP
A send error (\fISendReason\fR), indicates that the send function of the megaco transport callback module failed to send the request. There are two separate cases: \fISendCancelledReason\fR and \fISendFailedReason\fR. The first is the result of the send function returning \fI{cancel, Reason}\fR and the second is some other kind of erroneous return value. See the send_message function for more info.

.PP
An \fIOtherReason\fR, indicates some other error such as timeout.

.PP
For more info about the 'extra' part of the result (\fISuccessExtra\fR and \fIErrorExtra\fR), see the note in the user callback module documentation.


.RE
.B
\fBcancel(ConnHandle, CancelReason) -> ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                when\fR
\fB                    ConnHandle :: conn_handle(),\fR
\fB                    CancelReason :: term(),\fR
\fB                    Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Cancel all outstanding messages for this connection

.PP
This causes outstanding megaco:call/3 requests to return. The callback functions UserMod:handle_reply/4 and UserMod:handle_trans_ack/4 are also invoked where it applies. See the megaco_user module for more info about the callback arguments.


.RE
.B
\fBcast(ConnHandle, ActionRequests, SendOptions) ->\fR
\fB              ok | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  ConnHandle :: conn_handle(),\fR
\fB                  ActionRequests :: action_reqs() | [action_reqs()],\fR
\fB                  SendOptions :: [SendOption],\fR
\fB                  SendOption ::\fR
\fB                      {request_keep_alive_timeout,\fR
\fB                       RequestKeepAliveTimer} |\fR
\fB                      {request_timer, megaco_timer()} |\fR
\fB                      {long_request_timer, megaco_timer()} |\fR
\fB                      {send_handle, send_handle()} |\fR
\fB                      {reply_data, ReplyData} |\fR
\fB                      {protocol_version, ProtocolVersion},\fR
\fB                  RequestKeepAliveTimer :: plain | non_neg_integer(),\fR
\fB                  ReplyData :: term(),\fR
\fB                  ProtocolVersion :: protocol_version(),\fR
\fB                  Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Sends one or more transaction request(s) but does NOT wait for a reply

.PP
When sending one transaction in a message, \fIActionRequests\fR should be \fIaction_reqs/0\fR. When sending several transactions in a message, \fIActionRequests\fR should be \fI[action_reqs()]\fR. Each element of the list is part of one transaction.

.PP
For some of \fIour\fR codecs (not binary), it is also possible to pre-encode the actions, in which case \fIActions\fR will be either a \fIbinary/0\fR or \fI[binary()]\fR.

.PP
The default values of the send options are obtained by megaco:conn_info(ConnHandle, Item). But the send options above, may explicitly be overridden.

.PP
The ProtocolVersion version is the version actually encoded in the reply message.

.PP
The callback function UserMod:handle_trans_reply/4 is invoked when the reply arrives, when the request timer eventually times out or when the outstanding requests are explicitly cancelled. See the megaco_user module for more info about the callback arguments.

.PP
Given as \fIReplyData\fR argument to UserMod:handle_trans_reply/4.


.RE
.B
\fBconn_info(ConnHandle, ConnInfo) -> Value\fR
\fB                   when\fR
\fB                       ConnHandle :: conn_handle(),\fR
\fB                       ConnInfo ::\fR
\fB                           all | requests | replies | conn_info_item(),\fR
\fB                       Value :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Lookup information about an active connection

.PP
Requires that the connection is active.

.PP
Failure: \fIexit\fR if, for instance, \fIConnHandle\fR refers to a connection that no longer exists.


.RE
.B
\fBconnect(ReceiveHandle, RemoteMid, SendHandle, ControlPid, Extra) ->\fR
\fB                 {ok, ConnHandle} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                 when\fR
\fB                     ReceiveHandle :: receive_handle(),\fR
\fB                     RemoteMid :: preliminary_mid | mid(),\fR
\fB                     SendHandle :: send_handle(),\fR
\fB                     ControlPid :: pid(),\fR
\fB                     Extra :: term(),\fR
\fB                     ConnHandle :: conn_handle(),\fR
\fB                     Reason ::\fR
\fB                         ConnectReason | HandleConnectReason | term(),\fR
\fB                     ConnectReason ::\fR
\fB                         {no_such_user, LocalMid} |\fR
\fB                         {already_connected, ConnHandle} |\fR
\fB                         term(),\fR
\fB                     LocalMid :: mid(),\fR
\fB                     HandleConnectReason ::\fR
\fB                         {connection_refused, ConnData, ErrorInfo} |\fR
\fB                         term(),\fR
\fB                     ConnData :: term(),\fR
\fB                     ErrorInfo :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Establish a "virtual" connection

.PP
Activates a connection to a remote user. When this is done the connection can be used to send messages (with \fISendMod:send_message/2\fR). The \fIControlPid\fR is the identifier of a process that controls the connection. That process will be supervised and if it dies, this will be detected and the \fIUserMod:handle_disconnect/2\fR callback function will be invoked. See the megaco_user module for more info about the callback arguments. The connection may also explicitly be deactivated by invoking \fImegaco:disconnect/2\fR.

.PP
The \fIControlPid\fR may be the identity of a process residing on another Erlang node. This is useful when you want to distribute a user over several Erlang nodes. In such a case one of the nodes has the physical connection. When a user residing on one of the other nodes needs to send a request (with \fImegaco:call/3\fR or \fImegaco:cast/3\fR), the message will encoded on the originating Erlang node, and then be forwarded to the node with the physical connection. When the reply arrives, it will be forwarded back to the originator. The distributed connection may explicitly be deactivated by a local call to \fImegaco:disconnect/2\fR or implicitly when the physical connection is deactivated (with \fImegaco:disconnect/2\fR, killing the controlling process, halting the other node, ...).

.PP
The call of this function will trigger the callback function \fIUserMod:handle_connect/2\fR to be invoked. See the megaco_user module for more info about the callback arguments.

.PP
A connection may be established in several ways:

provisioned MID
.RS 2
The MG may explicitly invoke megaco:connect/4 and use a provisioned MID of the MGC as the RemoteMid.


.RE

upgrade preliminary MID
.RS 2
The MG may explicitly invoke megaco:connect/4 with the atom 'preliminary_mid' as a temporary MID of the MGC, send an intial message, the Service Change Request, to the MGC and then wait for an initial message, the Service Change Reply. When the reply arrives, the Megaco application will pick the MID of the MGC from the message header and automatically upgrade the connection to be a "normal" connection. By using this method of establishing the connection, the callback function 
\fIUserMod:handle_connect/2\fR to be invoked twice. First with a \fIConnHandle\fR with the remote_mid-field set to preliminary_mid, and then when the connection upgrade is done with the remote_mid-field set to the actual MID of the MGC.

.RE

automatic
.RS 2
When the MGC receives its first message, the Service Change Request, the Megaco application will automatically establish the connection by using the MG MID found in the message header as remote mid.


.RE

distributed
.RS 2
When a user (MG/MGC) is distributed over several nodes, it is required that the node hosting the connection already has activated the connection and that it is in the "normal" state. The 
\fIRemoteMid\fR must be a real Megaco MID and not a \fIpreliminary_mid\fR.

.RE

.PP
An initial megaco_receive_handle record may be obtained with \fImegaco:user_info(UserMid, receive_handle)\fR

.PP
The send handle is provided by the preferred transport module, e.g. megaco_tcp, megaco_udp. Read the documentation about each transport module about the details.

.PP
The connect is done in two steps: first an internal \fIconnection setup\fR and then by calling the user handle_connect callback function. The first step could result in an error with \fIReason = ConnectReason\fR and the second an error with \fIReason = HandleConnectReason\fR:

ConnectReason
.RS 2
An error with this reason is generated by the megaco application itself.


.RE

HandleConnectReason
.RS 2
An error with this reason is caused by the user handle_connect callback function either returning an error or an invalid value.


.RE

.PP
\fIExtra\fR can be any \fIterm/0\fR except the atom \fIignore_extra\fR. It is passed (back) to the user via the callback function handle_connect/3.


.RE
.B
\fBdecode_sdp(PP) -> {ok, SDP} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                    when\fR
\fB                        PP ::\fR
\fB                            property_parm() |\fR
\fB                            property_group() |\fR
\fB                            property_groups() |\fR
\fB                            asn1_NOVALUE,\fR
\fB                        SDP ::\fR
\fB                            sdp() |\fR
\fB                            DecodeSdpPropertyGroup |\fR
\fB                            DecodeSdpPropertyGroups | asn1_NOVALUE,\fR
\fB                        DecodeSdpPropertyGroup :: [DecodeSDP],\fR
\fB                        DecodeSdpPropertyGroups ::\fR
\fB                            [DecodeSdpPropertyGroup],\fR
\fB                        DecodeSDP ::\fR
\fB                            sdp() | {property_parm(), DecodeError},\fR
\fB                        DecodeError :: term(),\fR
\fB                        Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Decode (parse) a property parameter construct.

.PP
When decoding \fIproperty_group/0\fR or \fIproperty_groups/0\fR, those property parameter constructs that cannot be decoded (either because of decode error or because they are unknown), will be returned as a two-tuple. The first element of which will be the (undecoded) property parameter and the other the actual reason. This means that the caller of this function has to expect not only sdp-records, but also this two-tuple construct.

.PP
This function performs the following transformation:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
property_parm() -> sdp()

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
property_group() -> sdp_property_group()

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
property_groups() -> sdp_property_groups()

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBdisable_trace() -> void().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
This function is used to stop megaco tracing.


.RE
.B
\fBdisconnect(ConnHandle, DiscoReason) -> ok | {error, ErrReason}\fR
\fB                    when\fR
\fB                        ConnHandle :: conn_handle(),\fR
\fB                        DiscoReason :: term(),\fR
\fB                        ErrReason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Tear down a "virtual" connection

.PP
Causes the \fIUserMod:handle_disconnect/2\fR callback function to be invoked. See the megaco_user module for more info about the callback arguments.


.RE
.B
\fBenable_trace(Level, Destination) -> void()\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Level :: trace_level(),\fR
\fB                          Destination :: File | Port | HandlerSpec | io,\fR
\fB                          File :: string(),\fR
\fB                          Port :: integer(),\fR
\fB                          HandlerSpec :: {HandlerFun, InitialData},\fR
\fB                          HandlerFun :: trace_handler(),\fR
\fB                          InitialData :: trace_data().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
This function is used to start megaco tracing at a given \fILevel\fR and direct result to the given \fIDestination\fR.

.PP
It starts a tracer server and then sets the proper match spec (according to \fILevel\fR).

.PP
In the case when \fIDestination\fR is \fIFile\fR, the printable megaco trace events will be printed to the file \fIFile\fR using plain \fIio:format/2\fR.

.PP
In the case when \fIDestination\fR is \fIio\fR, the printable megaco trace events will be printed on stdout using plain \fIio:format/2\fR.

.PP
See \fIdbg\fR for further information.


.RE
.B
\fBencode_actions(ConnHandle, ActionRequests, Options) ->\fR
\fB                        {ok, Result} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                        when\fR
\fB                            ConnHandle :: conn_handle(),\fR
\fB                            ActionRequests ::\fR
\fB                                action_reqs() | [action_reqs()],\fR
\fB                            Options :: [Option],\fR
\fB                            Option ::\fR
\fB                                {request_timer, megaco_timer()} |\fR
\fB                                {long_request_timer, megaco_timer()} |\fR
\fB                                {send_handle, send_handle()} |\fR
\fB                                {protocol_version, protocol_version()},\fR
\fB                            Result :: binary() | [binary()],\fR
\fB                            Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Encodes lists of action requests for one or more transaction request(s).

.PP
When encoding action requests for one transaction, \fIActions\fR should be \fIaction_reqs/0\fR. When encoding action requests for several transactions, \fIActions\fR should be \fI[action_reqs()]\fR. Each element of the list is part of one transaction.


.RE
.B
\fBencode_sdp(SDP) -> {ok, PP} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                    when\fR
\fB                        SDP ::\fR
\fB                            sdp_property_parm() |\fR
\fB                            sdp_property_group() |\fR
\fB                            sdp_property_groups() |\fR
\fB                            asn1_NOVALUE,\fR
\fB                        PP ::\fR
\fB                            property_parm() |\fR
\fB                            property_group() |\fR
\fB                            property_groups() |\fR
\fB                            asn1_NOVALUE,\fR
\fB                        Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Encode (generate) an SDP construct.

.PP
If a \fIproperty_parm/0\fR is found as part of the input (\fISDP\fR) then it is left unchanged.

.PP
This function performs the following transformation:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
sdp() -> property_parm()

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
sdp_property_group() -> property_group()

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
sdp_property_groups() -> property_groups()

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBeval_digit_map(DigitMap, Timers) ->\fR
\fB                        {ok, MatchResult} | {error, Reason}\fR
\fB                        when\fR
\fB                            DigitMap ::\fR
\fB                                digit_map_value() | ParsedDigitMap,\fR
\fB                            ParsedDigitMap :: term(),\fR
\fB                            Timers :: Ignore | Reject,\fR
\fB                            Ignore ::\fR
\fB                                ignore | {ignore, digit_map_value()},\fR
\fB                            Reject ::\fR
\fB                                reject |\fR
\fB                                {reject, digit_map_value()} |\fR
\fB                                digit_map_value(),\fR
\fB                            MatchResult ::\fR
\fB                                {Kind, Letters} | {Kind, Letters, Extra},\fR
\fB                            Kind :: digit_map_kind(),\fR
\fB                            Letters :: [digit_map_letter()],\fR
\fB                            Extra :: digit_map_letter(),\fR
\fB                            Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Collect digit map letters according to the digit map.

.PP
When evaluating a digit map, a state machine waits for timeouts and letters reported by megaco:report_digit_event/2. The length of the various timeouts are defined in the digit_map_value() record.

.PP
When a complete sequence of valid events has been received, the result is returned as a list of letters.

.PP
There are two options for handling syntax errors (that is when an unexpected event is received when the digit map evaluator is expecting some other event). The unexpected events may either be ignored or rejected. The latter means that the evaluation is aborted and an error is returned.


.RE
